IRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Fenrother was born in 1458, in London, England as the son of Sir Fenrother. He married Lady Julian Sandes in 1479. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1524, in his hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1458–1524":"1458–1524","1480–1511":"1480–1511","1460–1524":"1460–1524","1503–1538":"1503–1538","1480–1536":"1480–1536","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1460":"1460","Abt 1510":"umbes 1510","1480":"1480","Abt 1503":"umbes 1503","after 1511":"pärast 1511","1536":"1536","1503":"1503","1458":"1458","1524":"1524","1479":"1479","1500":"1500","1511":"1511","1510":"1510","1430":"1430","1538":"1538","London, Greater London, England":"London, England","Christchurch, East Stour, Dorset, England":"Christ Church, East Stour, Dorset, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","Christchurch, Hampshire, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1458–1524":"1458–1524","1480–1511":"1480–